    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-58881">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-58881" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-58881">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-58881">Walt French</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-58881" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-58881" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>@johan Du Toit wrote, <i>“Sigh… You state that hardware prices fall over time. This is a misinterpretation of the law of commoditisation.”</i></p>
<p>Well, of course, commoditization doesn&#8217;t just happen because of time; it is caused by producers seeing an opportunity to gain business by producing an undifferentiated commodity. But especially in a business with rapidly-changing tech, businesses have to learn how to produce the new state-of-the-art products, design them, and ramp up production. All that takes time, so commoditization happens over time.</p>
<p>Or maybe I&#8217;m misinterpreting what you call the “law of commoditisation.” — Google dished up articles about commodities law and “how to keep your law practice from being commoditized” so please feel to express what this law represents if NOT the notion that disruptive changes are eventually suffused through an industry.</p>
<p>So no wonder you&#8217;re exasperated that we don&#8217;t get it: you&#8217;ve skipped the point you think we should understand.</p>
</div>
